= an open letter to the internet ========

dead-internet problem is real and serious

while most is often harmless detection is
to say the least hard to discern nowadays
but will not get easier with time either.

my first real realisation of this came at
the release of flux img gen model 1.1 dev
the images were grainy'ish, felt too real
notably one image of a family that stuck.

on social media my parents (in their 50s)
were already getting got, by not-so-great
posts clearly made with the help of AI...

writing was already submerged when edited
and even "detectors" were known for fails
original work being flagged. call-it-out:
culture, spiderman-meme where its hard to
tell what is genuine or complete bullshit

=========================================

the primitives of this failure are clear:
1. stake
engagement (views, likes)> training data$
2. proof
instead of trying to "detect" how fake XY

for a web-of-trust this means detection >
downstream and lossy, gets harder to tell
while realness provenance is upstream and
lossless. this is the only leverage left.
this means playing offense at the source.

=========================================

github, reddit, youtube, or most socials.
affected by an issue relatively simple to
predict was going to get worse and worse.

=========================================

2014 i was botting instagram accounts to:
1. barely respect rate limit for like/f2f
2. unfollow later, then rinse and repeat.

back then this was niche not v widespread
but today mimicry is easier, plus profits
follow these pattern of algorithmic games

the reward was "gameable" and engagements
were the direct reward of said trickeries

=========================================

the vicious cycle here is that a reaction
positive or negative is direct engagement
whether through automation abuse ragebait
low-effort sharing, it's all the same e2e

=========================================

can we make something genuine + unwitting
humans are not mislead by manifold strats

1. scale
small community = easy moderation targets
2. continuity
long history = easy to spot real interest
3. economics
less gamified = less of interest for bots

=========================================

provenance causes another issue by itself
closed-off communities where the barriers
to entry are too high but secures a scale
where reaction-is-engagement as positives

for existing large communities inherently
game-the-reward is already too prevelant.
a post or comment  presented amongst 100s
of others, is detached from it's history.
the platform itself is made for attention
by contrast, a smaller community, ermeges
trust through natural repeat interactions

=========================================

build environments where authenticity can
be established at all through time/trust. 
this also brings these to be more full of
context, and more genuine likeable ideas.

the real question is how does WoT welcome
isolated newcomer, no-network-yet person?

how do you make these gates keep out bots
but open-enough, for it not be a fortress

by letting trust grow, demanding up front
a door barely needs a lock but no looting

=========================================

how moderation is not about the contents.
or at least rarely, but about the history

no complex captchas or invasive questions
forms to fill and reasons justify at gate

=========================================

Numerous bots on github (worst on others)

1. Repo archives (mostly harmless)
2. Engage farms
3. Auto pull requests
4. Spread malware (as seen in HayDay)
5. Low-effort issues

For a dev it's relatively easy to tell...
But on socials that are already attention
grabbing algorithmic hell-holes, worsens.

========================================

RePaper: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2605.12512
